To prove this, we need to show that for any `y`, the value of the left side applied to `y` equals the value of the right side applied to `y`.

The left side applied to `y` is `(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha (m • x) y).integral f`.
The right side applied to `y` is `m • ((cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f)`.

So, we need to prove: `(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha (m • x) y).integral f = m • ((cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f)` for any `y`.

Looking at the definitions:
`cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y := ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)`

And `cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y := compSL C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) _ _ _ _ (toLinearFunctional x y) (cfcCLM ha)`

We need to show that `ComplexMeasure.integral (ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure ...) f` is linear in `x` with respect to the scalar multiplication by `m`.

This is a standard property of the Riesz-Markov-Kakutani theorem, where the integral is linear in the measure and the function. Since `cfc_toComplexMeasure` is defined as a measure, and `integral` is linear, we should be able to pull the scalar `m` out.

